<h2>HVAC Systems in New Jersey</h2>

<h3>Climate Considerations</h3>

<p>New Jersey's humid continental climate presents unique challenges and opportunities for HVAC system selection and operation. The state experiences four distinct seasons, with hot, humid summers averaging 75-85¬∞F and cold winters with temperatures frequently dropping below freezing. Summer humidity levels often exceed 70%, creating substantial cooling loads that require efficient dehumidification capabilities. Winter heating demands are significant, with heating degree days ranging from 4,500 in southern coastal areas to over 5,500 in northwestern mountainous regions.</p>

<p>The state's coastal influence moderates temperature extremes compared to inland areas, but also contributes to higher humidity levels that affect both comfort and HVAC system performance. Air conditioning systems in New Jersey must be properly sized to handle both sensible cooling loads (temperature reduction) and latent cooling loads (moisture removal). Oversized systems often fail to adequately dehumidify indoor air, leading to comfort issues and potential indoor air quality problems.</p>

<p>Heating system selection in New Jersey depends largely on available fuel sources and local utility costs. Natural gas remains the most common heating fuel, available through PSE&G and other utilities in most urban and suburban areas. Heat pump technology has gained popularity due to improved cold-weather performance and potential integration with solar panel systems. Modern cold-climate heat pumps can operate efficiently down to -5¬∞F, making them viable for most New Jersey locations when properly sized and installed.</p>

