<h2>New Jersey Incentives & Rebates</h2>

<p>New Jersey offers one of the most comprehensive renewable energy incentive programs in the United States, making solar panel installations and energy-efficient HVAC systems highly attractive investments. The federal solar Investment Tax Credit (ITC) provides a 30% tax credit for solar panel installations through 2032, with the credit stepping down to 26% in 2033 and 22% in 2034. This credit applies to the total installed cost of the system, including equipment, installation, and applicable sales taxes, and can be carried forward to future tax years if not fully utilized in the installation year.</p>

<p>The state's Solar Renewable Energy Certificate (SREC) program provides ongoing payments for solar energy production, with system owners receiving one SREC for every 1,000 kWh of electricity generated. New Jersey's SREC market typically values these certificates between \$85-\$220 each, depending on market conditions and program requirements. A typical 8kW residential system producing 10,000 kWh annually would generate 10 SRECs, providing \$850-\$2,200 in additional annual income for 15 years under the current SREC-II program.</p>

<p>PSE&G offers additional rebates through their Clean Energy Future programs, including rebates up to \$4,000 for ENERGY STAR certified heat pump installations and up to \$1,200 for high-efficiency central air conditioning systems. The utility also provides interest-free financing options for qualified energy efficiency improvements, making it easier for customers to invest in premium HVAC equipment. Net metering regulations allow solar panel owners to receive full retail credit for excess electricity exported to the grid, effectively using the utility grid as a battery system during periods of low solar production.</p>

<p>New Jersey's Clean Energy Program, administered by the Board of Public Utilities, provides additional rebates for residential energy efficiency improvements. These include rebates up to \$5,000 for geothermal heat pump installations and various rebates for ductless mini-split systems, smart thermostats, and whole-house energy audits. Many municipalities also offer property tax exemptions for solar panel installations, ensuring that the added home value from solar systems doesn't increase property tax assessments.</p>

